<h2 id="what-easy-read-is">What Easy Read is</h2>
<p>Easy Read is an accessible communication format designed to reduce the cognitive effort needed to find, process and act on information. It combines concise language, predictable structure and meaningful images so each idea is easier to understand and remember.</p>
<p>It is particularly useful for people with intellectual disability, learning disability or other cognitive disability, and people with low literacy. It can also support older people and people who are learning English. Its purpose is to give people greater independence when making decisions, staying safe and accessing government services.</p>
<p>The method brings together three connected elements:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Information architecture:</strong> organise Easy Read information into landing, category and detail pages so people can find a topic and move to the article they need.</li>
  <li><strong>Image-and-text content blocks:</strong> pair one concept or action with a meaningful image and supporting text. This is the commonly recognised Easy Read content format.</li>
  <li><strong>Page content:</strong> apply <code>nsw-easy-read-content</code> to the complete Easy Read page or section. This scopes the larger typography and content spacing without changing the rest of the site.</li>
</ul>
<p>See the <a href="/templates/content/easy-read/detail.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">detail article template with illustrations</a> for a complete Easy Read page example.</p>

<h2 id="usage">Usage</h2>

<h3 id="when-to-use">When to use it</h3>
<p>Use Easy Read when research shows that the audience needs or prefers it, particularly for information about:</p>
<ul>
  <li>rights, choices and responsibilities</li>
  <li>health, safety and emergencies</li>
  <li>accessing services or support</li>
  <li>completing an important task, form or application</li>
  <li>changes that affect a person's daily life.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="when-not-to-use">When not to use it</h3>
<p>Do not use Easy Read by default when audience research does not support it, or when simplifying the information would remove detail people need to make a safe or informed decision.</p>
<p>Easy Read does not replace clear standard content, specialist translations, Auslan, audio, accessible documents or personalised support when users need those formats.</p>

<h2 id="information-architecture">Information architecture</h2>
<figure class="nsw-easy-read-ia">
  <ol class="nsw-easy-read-ia__list">
    <li>
      <div class="nsw-easy-read-ia__node nsw-easy-read-ia__node--landing">
        <strong>Landing page</strong>
        <span>Shows all available topics.</span>
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <div class="nsw-easy-read-ia__node nsw-easy-read-ia__node--child nsw-easy-read-ia__node--category">
            <strong>Category page</strong>
            <span>Lists the detail articles for one topic.</span>
          </div>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <div class="nsw-easy-read-ia__node nsw-easy-read-ia__node--child nsw-easy-read-ia__node--detail">
                <strong>Detail article</strong>
                <span>Provides the Easy Read information.</span>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>
  </ol>
  <figcaption>Easy Read uses a simple three-level content hierarchy.</figcaption>
</figure>
<ul>
  <li>Do not add another category level by default.</li>
  <li>Use breadcrumbs on category and detail pages.</li>
  <li>Link topics directly from the landing page.</li>
  <li>List articles directly from their category page.</li>
  <li>Provide a “Back to all Easy Read topics” link on category pages.</li>
  <li>Use the final About Easy Read callout to link people to more Easy Read articles.</li>
  <li>Avoid generic Previous and Next links or any arbitrary linear sequence.</li>
  <li>Only use sequence navigation for a genuine ordered process. Show progress and meaningful destination titles when you do.</li>
</ul>

