<h2 id="testing-and-review">Testing and review</h2>
<p>Use a multi-stage review: content self-review, peer review, accessibility review and usability testing. Include people with intellectual disability and other people from the identified audience. Pay them for their expertise and allow enough time and support for meaningful participation.</p>
<p>Test the complete experience, not isolated sentences. Check comprehension, image meaning, navigation, links, downloads and the read aloud function when it is implemented.</p>

<h2 id="accessibility-requirements">Accessibility requirements</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Use semantic headings in a logical hierarchy. Content-block titles default to H2 and only allow H3 as a controlled alternative.</li>
  <li>Provide meaningful alternative text for every informative image and explicitly mark decorative images.</li>
  <li>Keep the reading and focus order consistent with the visual order.</li>
  <li>Use descriptive links and visible keyboard focus.</li>
  <li>Support keyboard-only use, screen readers and text resizing to 200%.</li>
  <li>Verify reflow at a 320 CSS pixel viewport and at 400% browser zoom. Where testing identifies a layout or usability issue, use the <a href="/docs/content/utilities/reflow.html">Reflow Sass mixin</a> for a targeted component adjustment.</li>
  <li>Test light, dark and inverted themes without relying on colour alone.</li>
  <li>Keep accessible HTML as the primary format even when documents or a read aloud function are available.</li>
</ul>
